      <!-- INTRO -->
      <section id="intro" style="padding: 0; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <p>
          The **FIFA World Cup 2034** in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia stands as one of the most historic milestones in modern sporting history. It will represent the first time that a single nation hosts the expanded, **48-team tournament** in its entirety in the Middle East. Spanning across a diverse geographic landscape, from the high-altitude mountains of Abha to the hyper-futuristic linear city of NEOM, the 2034 tournament will showcase the absolute pinnacle of football competition. A total of **104 matches** will be played, uniting players and fans from every corner of the globe in a celebration of sport, culture, and hospitality.
        </p>
        <p>
          The scale of this tournament is unprecedented. Moving away from the traditional 32-team format, the 48-team structure means that the tournament will run over a longer duration of approximately 38 to 40 days. The teams will be divided into 12 groups of four, with the top two teams from each group, along with the eight best third-placed teams, advancing to a newly introduced Round of 32. This expansion increases the total number of matches from 64 to 104, necessitating a massive logistical footprint that only a nation with the strategic focus of Saudi Arabia can deliver. Every match day will present multiple high-stakes fixtures, turning the entire country into an active, high-performance sports arena.
        </p>
        <p>
          Saudi Arabia's successful bid is the crowning achievement of the country's **Vision 2030** transformation program. Under this national roadmap, the Kingdom is opening its doors to international tourism, building carbon-neutral cities, and investing billions in sports and cultural infrastructure. The 2034 World Cup is not just a sporting event; it is the ultimate showcase of a nation redefining its position on the global stage. For the traveler, this means access to newly constructed high-speed rail lines, futuristic metro networks, brand-new airports, and world-class hotels that have been designed to meet the highest standards of international luxury and sustainability.
        </p>
        <p>
          The tournament is scheduled to take place during the winter months of **November and December 2034**. This timing replicates the climatic success of the Qatar 2022 World Cup, ensuring that matches are played in mild, pleasant weather. During this period, temperatures across most of the host cities range between a comfortable 15°C and 25°C (59°F to 77°F), which is optimal for stadium attendance, outdoor fan festivals, and sightseeing. This guide serves as your comprehensive, independent handbook, providing detailed logistics, transport schedules, cultural rules, and local advice to ensure an unforgettable World Cup journey.
        </p>
        <p>
          As a central hub for all things football-related in the Kingdom, this page links directly to specialized "Spoke" pages covering stadium-specific details, hotel guides, and transit applications. Whether you are planning to follow your national team through the group stages or securing tickets for the historic Final, the following sections provide the granular detail required to navigate the Kingdom during this month-long celebration.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- HOST CITIES & STADIUMS -->
      <section id="host-cities" style="padding: 0; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2>Host Cities &amp; Their Stadiums</h2>
        <p>
          Saudi Arabia's tournament master plan features **15 state-of-the-art stadiums** located across **8 distinct host cities**. Each city offers a unique environment, reflecting the diverse geography and culture of the Kingdom. The matches are strategically distributed to minimize travel times for teams and fans, grouping matches by geographical clusters. This regional grouping ensures that fans can base themselves in a single city or cluster for the group stages, reducing the need for constant, long-distance travel.
        </p>
        <p>
          Riyadh, the capital, serves as the main anchor of the tournament, hosting the opening and final matches. Jeddah, the gateway to the Red Sea, offers coastal stadium atmospheres and deep historical excursions. Meanwhile, the mountain city of Abha provides high-altitude stadium conditions, and the futuristic NEOM presents a venue suspended 350 meters above the ground. Below is the official breakdown of the host cities, stadium names, capacities, and match distributions:
        </p>

