        <p>
          Each of these venues is being constructed or upgraded to conform to the highest standards of energy efficiency. The newly designed stadiums, such as the Aramco Stadium in Al Khobar and the Prince Mohammed bin Salman Stadium in Qiddiya, feature revolutionary architectural elements. The Qiddiya stadium, for example, is perched on the edge of a 200-meter cliff, featuring a LED wall that opens up to offer panoramic views of the entertainment city below. The NEOM Stadium is integrated directly into the vertical modules of *The Line*, powered entirely by renewable wind and solar energy, representing a landmark achievement in sustainable sports design.
        </p>

        <h3>Riyadh Venues</h3>
        <p>
          Riyadh will serve as the administrative and competitive core of the tournament. The **King Salman International Stadium** stands as the crown jewel of the host venues. With a massive capacity of over 92,000, it is designed to host the historic Opening Match and the Grand Final. The stadium's architecture incorporates local green corridors and solar infrastructure, integrating seamlessly with the Green Riyadh initiative. The renovated **King Fahd International Stadium** (capacity 67,000) features an iconic tent-like fabric roof that has dominated Riyadh's eastern skyline for decades, now updated with modern media, VIP hospitality, and skywalk transit links. **Al-Awwal Park** (capacity 25,000), located on the King Saud University campus, will offer an intimate, high-energy environment for group stage matches, while the **Prince Faisal bin Fahd Stadium** (capacity 45,000) will benefit from deep-city transit links. Finally, the **Prince Mohammed bin Salman Stadium** in the futuristic entertainment city of Qiddiya represents the next generation of sports architecture, perched atop the Tuwaiq cliffside.
        </p>

        <h3>Jeddah Venues</h3>
        <p>
          Jeddah, located on the Red Sea coast, offers a different atmosphere, combining maritime culture with football passion. The **King Abdullah Sports City**, locally known as "The Shining Jewel," has a capacity of 62,241 and is the home of Jeddah's football legacy. It features a stunning geometric facade that glows at night, mimicking local Islamic art. It will host matches up to the Semi-Final stage. The new **Jeddah Central Stadium** (capacity 45,000) is part of a massive waterfront redevelopment project, integrating stadium visits with yacht marinas, public beaches, and the historic Al-Balad district.
        </p>

        <h3>Eastern Province: Al Khobar &amp; Dammam</h3>
        <p>
          The Eastern Province, facing the Arabian Gulf, will act as a major entry point for fans traveling from neighboring GCC countries. The **Aramco Stadium** in Al Khobar (capacity 47,000) is a new build featuring a wave-like facade inspired by the Gulf waters. It will host matches up to the Quarter-Finals. Dammam will support the cluster with two venues: the renovated **Prince Mohamed bin Fahd Stadium** (capacity 30,000) and the brand-new **Dammam Arena Stadium** (capacity 40,000). This cluster is highly accessible, linked directly to Bahrain via the King Fahd Causeway, allowing international fans to split their stay between the two nations.
        </p>

        <h3>Specialist Venues: NEOM, Abha, Madinah, Tabuk</h3>
        <p>
          These four cities introduce unique geographical elements to the tournament. The **NEOM Stadium** is perhaps the most futuristic venue ever proposed for a World Cup. Built into the structure of *The Line*, the stadium is suspended 350 meters above the ground, offering spectators views of the surrounding desert canyon and Red Sea coast. It is designed to be carbon-neutral and fully powered by renewable energy. The **King Khalid University Stadium** in Abha (capacity 45,000) is located in the Sarawat Mountains at an altitude of 2,200 meters. The cool highland climate will offer a spring-like setting, though teams will need to adjust to the high-altitude conditions. Madinah's **Prince Mohammed bin Abdulaziz Stadium** (capacity 40,000) will welcome fans to one of the world's most significant historical cities, while Tabuk's **King Khalid Sports City Stadium** (capacity 30,000) will act as a key gateway in the northwest, close to the Red Sea luxury resorts.
        </p>
