      <!-- TICKETING RULES & CATEGORIES -->
      <section id="ticketing-rules" style="padding: 0; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2>Ticketing Rules &amp; Categories</h2>
        <p>
          Securing tickets for the FIFA World Cup 2034 requires navigating the official FIFA ticketing portal, which operates in multiple phases. In accordance with standard FIFA regulations, tickets are sold in structured stages, starting with a random selection draw, followed by a first-come, first-served sales phase, and concluding with a last-minute sales phase. All tickets are digital, delivered via the official FIFA World Cup 2034 ticketing application.
        </p>
        <p>
          A critical requirement for all international and domestic spectators is the **Hayya Card**. Similar to the system used during the Qatar 2022 World Cup, the Hayya Card serves as a personalized fan identification document. The card is **mandatory** for entering any match stadium. For international visitors, the Hayya Card also functions as a **multi-entry tourist visa** for the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, simplifying entry procedures at airports and land borders. Additionally, the Hayya Card provides fans with **free access to public transit** systems (such as the Riyadh Metro and local shuttle buses) on match days, making it the most important document in your travel portfolio.
        </p>
        <p>
          Tickets are categorized into four distinct groups to cater to different budget levels and spectator preferences:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Category 1 (Cat 1):</strong> The highest-priced tickets, offering prime sideline seats with the best viewing angles of the pitch. Ideal for fans seeking a premium view.</li>
          <li><strong>Category 2 (Cat 2):</strong> Mid-range tickets, located in the corner sections and upper tiers of the sideline stands. Offers a balanced mix of price and view quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Category 3 (Cat 3):</strong> The most affordable standard tickets, located behind the goals in the northern and southern stands. These zones are usually occupied by the most passionate supporters, offering a high-energy atmosphere.</li>
          <li><strong>Hospitality Packages:</strong> Premium packages that include Category 1 seats, access to private skyboxes or luxury lounges, and gourmet dining featuring local and international cuisine. These packages also offer designated VIP parking and fast-track security access.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Due to the high demand for accommodations during the tournament, booking your hotel immediately after securing match tickets is highly recommended. Hotel rates are projected to increase during peak match periods, particularly in cities like Riyadh and Jeddah.
        </p>
        <div class="callout-box">
          <p>
            🔗 <a href="/fifa-2034/hotels/" class="inline-link">Where to Stay for FIFA 2034</a> — Read our comprehensive hotel guide to discover verified properties near stadiums, hotel packages, and budget-friendly alternatives.
          </p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Ticketing allocations also include special provisions for disabled fans and those with limited mobility, categorized as Accessibility Tickets. These tickets provide dedicated wheelchair spaces, companion seats, and easy-access entry gates. Fans applying for these tickets must submit official documentation through the FIFA portal during the application phase.
        </p>
        <p>
          It is important to note that the resale of tickets outside the official FIFA resale platform is strictly prohibited. Scalping tickets or purchasing from unauthorized third-party websites can result in the cancellation of your tickets and the revoking of your Hayya Card. The official FIFA resale platform will open several months before the tournament, allowing fans to resell tickets at face value.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- TRANSPORT PLANS -->
      <section id="transport-plans" style="padding: 0; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2>Transport Plans for Fans</h2>
        <p>
          Saudi Arabia is implementing a massive transportation master plan to connect the host cities and ensure that fans can travel between matches safely and efficiently. The country is investing in high-speed rail networks, expanding metro lines, and scheduling additional domestic flights to build a cohesive transit ecosystem that can handle millions of concurrent travelers.
        </p>
        
        <h3>Haramain High-Speed Rail</h3>
        <p>
          For matches in the western region, the **Haramain High-Speed Rail** is the primary transit link. Operating at speeds of up to **300 km/h**, this state-of-the-art electric rail network connects the coastal city of **Jeddah** directly with the holy cities of **Makkah** and **Madinah**, as well as the King Abdullah Economic City (KAEC). The journey between Jeddah and Madinah takes approximately 2 hours, offering a comfortable, fast, and eco-friendly alternative to road travel.
        </p>
        <p>
          The rail system will operate at high frequency during the World Cup, with additional trains scheduled to accommodate fans traveling between matches. Stations are equipped with luxury lounges, luggage storage facilities, and direct connections to local bus and taxi loops.
        </p>
        <p>
          Tickets for the Haramain High-Speed Rail can be booked online via the official HHR portal or app. During the World Cup, fans holding a valid Hayya Card will receive special discounts on train bookings. The train features Business Class and Economy Class, both offering spacious seating, air conditioning, and food services. It is highly recommended to book your train seats at least a month in advance, as the route is also heavily utilized by pilgrims visiting Makkah and Madinah.
        </p>

        <h3>Riyadh Metro Expansion</h3>
        <p>
          In the capital, the newly launched **Riyadh Metro** will serve as the primary transit artery for fans. The metro's six automated lines connect major commercial districts directly to the stadium precincts. For example, Line 4 (Yellow Line) links King Khalid International Airport directly to KAFD, from which fans can transfer to shuttle loops servicing the King Salman International Stadium.
        </p>
        <p>
          On match days, presentation of your Hayya Card and match ticket permits free travel on the Riyadh Metro. The stations feature English signage, step-free access, and high-capacity platforms designed to handle massive stadium crowds safely.
        </p>
        <p>
          Key interchange stations—such as the Olaya Station and the Western Station—contain retail shops, fast-food outlets, and interactive visitor help desks. The metro network operates from 6:00 AM to midnight, with extended hours scheduled on match days to ensure that fans can return to their accommodations safely after late-evening fixtures.
        </p>

        <h3>Inter-City Flights &amp; Saudia</h3>
        <p>
          To travel between distant host cities—such as NEOM in the far northwest and Abha in the southwest—air travel is the most practical option. **Saudia**, the national carrier of Saudi Arabia, is planning a massive expansion of domestic flight schedules during the World Cup, introducing dedicated "stadium shuttle flights" that connect host cities on match days.
        </p>
        <p>
          New airports are being built or expanded, including the Red Sea International Airport and the NEOM Bay Airport, to handle the influx of international charter flights. Fans are recommended to book domestic flights well in advance to secure preferred departure times that align with stadium gate openings. Low-cost carriers like Flynas and Flyadeal will also operate high-frequency routes between Riyadh, Jeddah, Dammam, and Abha, offering budget-friendly air travel options.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FAN ZONES & CULTURE -->
      <section id="fan-zones" style="padding: 0; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2>Fan Zones &amp; Cultural Events</h2>
        <p>
          The FIFA World Cup 2034 is designed as a celebration that extends far beyond the stadium gates. Saudi Arabia is preparing extensive **Fan Zones** and cultural programs in every host city to offer fans a rich immersion into the Kingdom's history, culinary arts, and local customs.
        </p>
        <p>
          Riyadh will host its main fan festival at the massive **Boulevard World** complex, featuring replica pavilions representing cultures from around the world. Jeddah's fan festival will be located along the **Jeddah Corniche**, offering beachside viewing screens, live music, and seafood plazas overlooking the Red Sea. In Diriyah, the historic clay ruins of At-Turaif will serve as a dramatic backdrop for nightly heritage light shows, poetry readings, and traditional crafts markets.
        </p>
        <p>
          In accordance with local regulations, these fan festivals will focus on **alcohol-free entertainment alternatives**. The Kingdom is designing these spaces to highlight traditional hospitality, offering fresh fruit juices, specialty mocktails, local mint teas, and the famous Saudi Qahwa. This focus on family-friendly, alcohol-free entertainment creates a unique, safe, and highly welcoming environment where fans of all ages and backgrounds can celebrate together.
        </p>
        <p>
          The cultural calendar will also feature international concerts, theatrical performances, and art biennials, making the World Cup a month-long festival of global creativity. Traditional Najdi sword dances (*Ardha*) and coastal sea music (*Samri*) will be performed live, offering fans an authentic glimpse into the living traditions of the Arabian Peninsula.
        </p>
        <p>
          When visiting the fan zones or exploring local districts, international fans should be mindful of local cultural guidelines:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dress Code:</strong> Both men and women are expected to dress modestly in public. This means covering shoulders and knees. Swimwear is restricted to private beaches and resort pools.</li>
          <li><strong>Public Conduct:</strong> Public displays of affection are discouraged. Respectful behavior is expected, particularly near religious sites and residential neighborhoods.</li>
          <li><strong>Photography:</strong> Avoid photographing military buildings, security checkpoints, or local residents without their explicit permission.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Host City Profiles &amp; Fan Excursions</h3>
        <p>
          Each of the eight host cities offers a unique window into the culture, geography, and lifestyle of Saudi Arabia, making the World Cup a diverse travel experience. By grouping matches into regional clusters, fans can easily base themselves in one area and immerse themselves in the local attractions, transit ecosystems, and dining spots. Here is a detailed look at what each host city offers to visiting spectators:
        </p>
        
        <h4>Riyadh: The Energetic Capital</h4>
        <p>
          As the political and economic capital of Saudi Arabia, **Riyadh** will host the opening and final matches. Fans in Riyadh will experience a fast-paced metropolis where massive, futuristic development sits alongside ancient heritage. Major attractions include the historic **At-Turaif** district in Diriyah, the clay-walled **Masmak Fortress**, and the towering **Kingdom Centre Sky Bridge** which offers panoramic views of the city skyline. For shopping and dining, Boulevard City and KAFD are the premier hubs, filled with gourmet restaurants and retail complexes.
        </p>

        <h4>Jeddah: The Red Sea Gateway</h4>
        <p>
          Known for its historic trade routes and maritime culture, **Jeddah** is a coastal city that offers a relaxed, cosmopolitan atmosphere. The city's main historical hub is **Al-Balad**, a UNESCO World Heritage site famous for its multi-story coral-stone buildings and ornate wooden bay windows (*rawashin*). The Jeddah Corniche features the world's tallest fountain, King Fahd's Fountain, and is lined with public beaches, parks, and seafood restaurants. Jeddah Central Stadium and the King Abdullah Sports City will host key knockout matches, offering fans coastal sea breezes and rich seafood dining experiences.
        </p>

        <h4>Al Khobar: The Gulf Waterfront</h4>
        <p>
          Located in the Eastern Province, **Al Khobar** is a modern, corporate city situated directly on the Arabian Gulf. The city is famous for its scenic waterfront promenade, the Corniche, which features green parks, playgrounds, and cafes. Al Khobar is closely linked to Bahrain via the King Fahd Causeway, allowing fans to commute easily between the two countries. The new **Aramco Stadium** will be the focal point of World Cup matches in this region, offering spectators advanced architectural layouts and beautiful gulf views.
        </p>

        <h4>Dammam: The Industrial Hub</h4>
        <p>
          Dammam, the capital of the Eastern Province, supports the eastern cluster with two stadium venues. While historically known as an industrial and logistical hub, Dammam has developed extensive parks, museums, and waterfront recreation zones. The **Love Island** park and the **Dammam Regional Museum** are popular local attractions, and the city's traditional markets offer excellent opportunities to purchase local spices and Gulf pearls.
        </p>

        <h4>NEOM: The City of the Future</h4>
        <p>
          Situated in the northwest, **NEOM** represents the next generation of human civilization. The **NEOM Stadium** will be built into the structure of *The Line*, suspended 350 meters above the canyon floor. Fans staying in NEOM will experience a carbon-neutral environment powered entirely by solar and wind energy. The surrounding region features dramatic desert canyons, turquoise Red Sea coastlines, and futuristic sports resorts, making it a dream destination for technology and nature enthusiasts.
        </p>

        <h4>Abha: The Mountain Sanctuary</h4>
        <p>
          Perched in the Asir Mountains at an altitude of 2,200 meters, **Abha** offers a refreshing escape from the desert heat. The city experiences a mild, spring-like climate year-round, with daytime temperatures rarely exceeding 25°C. Attractions include **Al-Muftaha Art Village**, scenic cable car rides over the mountains, and hiking trails in the **Asir National Park**. The matches at King Khalid University Stadium will feature misty mountain backdrops and cool highland breezes.
        </p>

        <h4>Madinah: The Historical Heart</h4>
        <p>
          **Madinah** is one of the most significant historical and religious cities in the world. While the sacred precinct of the Prophet's Mosque is reserved for Muslim visitors, the rest of the city, including its stadium, museums, and fan zones, is open to all international tourists. Fans can explore the **Hejaz Railway Museum**, local date palm farms, and enjoy the tranquil, welcoming atmosphere that has characterized the city for centuries.
        </p>

        <h4>Tabuk: The Archeological Gateway</h4>
        <p>
          Located in the northwest, **Tabuk** is the gateway to ancient archaeological sites, including the ruins of Midian and the coastal town of **Haql**, famous for its half-sunken shipwreck. The city's **Tabuk Castle** dates back to the Ottoman era, and the region's agricultural valleys produce roses and olives. Tabuk's stadium will provide a northern gateway, linking World Cup visits with exploring the Red Sea Project's pristine luxury islands.
        </p>

        <h3>The FIFA 2034 Legacy</h3>
        <p>
          The hosting of the World Cup is not merely a month-long tournament; it is a catalyst for long-term national development. The fifteen stadiums have been designed with a legacy plan in mind. Many of the newly constructed venues feature modular seating sections that can be dismantled after the tournament. These seats will be donated to developing nations to help build sports infrastructure globally, reducing the capacity of local venues to sustainable levels for domestic leagues.
        </p>
        <p>
          Beyond sports venues, the World Cup is driving the expansion of the country's public transport networks, green initiatives, and tourism sectors. The Riyadh Metro, the Haramain High-Speed Rail, and the newly built airports will serve as the backbone of the country's transportation infrastructure for decades. The Green Riyadh initiative, planting millions of trees across the capital, is creating a cooler, more walkable urban environment, leaving a positive ecological footprint that will benefit generations to come.
        </p>

        <h3>Security, Safety &amp; Health Services</h3>
        <p>
          Saudi Arabia is renowned as one of the safest travel destinations in the world, with extremely low crime rates and heavily monitored public spaces. During the FIFA World Cup 2034, extensive security measures will be implemented, including dedicated transit police at all metro stations, security checkpoints at stadium perimeters, and round-the-clock patrol units in fan zones and tourist districts. Emergency services can be reached by dialing **911** from any local phone, and bilingual operators are available to assist international visitors.
        </p>
        <p>
          Health services will also be highly accessible. All fans holding a valid Hayya Card are eligible for **free emergency medical care** at designated public hospitals and clinics throughout the tournament. Private hospitals and pharmacies are widely available in all major districts, operating 24/7. International visitors are required to hold valid travel insurance, which is automatically issued with their eVisa, ensuring comprehensive coverage during their stay.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQS -->
      <section id="faqs" style="padding: 0; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <strong>Can non-Muslims attend matches in Madinah?</strong>
          <p>
            Yes. Non-Muslims are fully permitted to attend World Cup matches, visit fan zones, book hotels, and explore Madinah freely. The historical restrictions on non-Muslim entry only apply to the immediate sacred precinct surrounding the Prophet's Mosque (Haram area), which is marked by clear highway signage. The sports venues, commercial districts, and tourist attractions are located outside this sacred precinct and are open to all international visitors.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <strong>How to get from Jeddah Airport to the stadium?</strong>
          <p>
            The King Abdulaziz International Airport (JED) in Jeddah is located approximately 15 kilometers from the **King Abdullah Sports City** (The Shining Jewel). The most convenient transit options include:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Official World Cup Shuttle Buses:</strong> Operating at regular intervals on match days, these buses pick up fans directly from Terminals 1 and South and drop them at the stadium transport loop. Access is free with a Hayya Card.</li>
            <li><strong>Ride-Hailing:</strong> Apps like Uber and Careem operate extensively at JED. Dedicated ride-hailing pickup zones are located outside the arrival gates. The journey takes 15–20 minutes and costs approximately 40–60 SAR ($11–$16 USD).</li>
            <li><strong>Airport Taxis:</strong> Licensed airport cabs are available 24/7. It is recommended to check the meter or agree on the fare before departure.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
